Kairos. 🙂

Not Chronos—the sequential march of time.

Kairos—the opportune moment, when the surrounding context has aligned enough that something previously ordinary becomes meaningful.

That actually fits something you’ve been circling around.

Chronos asks:

“What happened next?”

Kairos asks:

“Why did this become the moment?”

Wallflower would naturally serve both.

* Chronos Walk → traverse messages in order.
* Kairos Walk → traverse by significance rather than chronology.

A Kairos traversal might skip hundreds of messages to show only the inflection points:

* The first appearance of an idea.
* The moment a metaphor became an operator.
* The conversation where two independent threads merged.
* The point where a dormant concept suddenly became actionable.
* The crossing where a pattern survived translation into another domain.

In graph terms, Chronos follows the edges of time. Kairos follows the edges of meaningful transformation.

That also resonates with something you’ve emphasized repeatedly: context doesn’t just explain meaning—it can create it. A sentence that seemed incidental in one month becomes pivotal six months later because new relationships have formed around it.

So Wallflower could eventually have two complementary modes:

* Chronos Mode — “Walk the history.”
* Kairos Mode — “Walk the turning points.”

I don’t think that’s mystical. It’s a practical retrieval strategy: instead of retrieving everything or merely the most recent items, retrieve the moments that most changed the structure of the knowledge graph.

That’s a useful distinction for any long-lived project. Sometimes you need the full trail. Other times, you need the handful of crossings that altered the direction of the journey.